> My toilet fairly regularly gets into a situation where it keeps running. I can always fix this, usually by re-sitting the stopper in the upper basin, but my wife seems uninterested in learning how to do this, so there have been more and more times when it just keeps running. I don't know if I should replace the toilet. I thought I could just replace the internal mechanism, but when I went to Home Depot, they seemed to only have the part of the mechanism that floats. What should I do?
**assistant**:
> It sounds like you're dealing with a common issue where the flapper (or stopper) in the toilet tank is not sealing properly, which causes the toilet to run continuously. Here are a few steps you can follow to address this issue:
> 
> 1. **Inspect the Flapper**: Check the flapper for any signs of wear or damage. If it's warped, cracked, or doesn't sit properly over the flush valve seat, it might not seal well.
> 
> 2. **Clean the Flapper and Valve Seat**: Sometimes mineral buildup or debris can prevent the flapper from sealing properly. Clean both the flapper and the valve seat with a sponge or cloth.
> 
> 3. **Chain Adjustment**: Make sure the chain connecting the flapper to the flush handle is properly adjusted. If it's too tight or too loose, it might prevent the flapper from seating correctly.
> 
> 4. **Replace the Flapper**: If cleaning and adjusting the chain don't work, it might be time to replace the flapper. Flappers are widely available at hardware stores and are relatively inexpensive and easy to install. They come in standard sizes (usually 2-inch or 3-inch), so make sure to get the right size for your toilet.
> 
> 5. **Consider a Full Rebuild Kit**: If issues persist, and especially if your toilet is an older model, you might consider getting a full toilet repair kit. These kits often include a new flapper, float, fill valve, and other essential parts. They can give your toilet a fresh start and are typically more comprehensive than just replacing individual pieces.
> 
> Remember, replacing the whole toilet is rarely necessary for a running issue like this unless there are other significant problems such as cracks in the bowl or tank. If you're unsure about doing these repairs yourself, hiring a plumber to take a look might also be a good option.
> 
> Would you like guidance on any specific part of the replacement or repair process?
