> To determine whether you need a 2-inch or 3-inch flapper repair kit, you can follow these steps:
> 
> 1. **Check the Existing Flapper**: 
>    - Remove the tank lid and inspect the flapper located at the bottom of the tank.
>    - Measure the diameter of the flush valve opening where the flapper sits. 
> 
> 2. **Size Identification**:
>    - **2-Inch**: Most older toilets and many standard models typically use a 2-inch flapper.
>    - **3-Inch**: Some newer models and high-efficiency toilets (HETs) feature a 3-inch flush valve for better performance.
> 
> 3. **Visual Comparison**: 
>    - If you’re unsure, take the existing flapper to the store for comparison, or check for markings on the flapper itself that might indicate the size.
> 
> 4. **Model Information**:
>    - You can also check the manufacturer’s information on your toilet, which is often stamped on the inside of the tank or on a label. This can help pinpoint the correct part size.
> 
> 5. **Ask for Help**: 
>    - If you’re at the store and still unsure, don't hesitate to ask a staff member for assistance. They can help you find the right repair kit based on what you’ve observed.
> 
> Choosing the right size is crucial for ensuring a proper seal and preventing the running issue from recurring. If all else fails, a universal repair kit may be a flexible option, as it usually includes adapters for different sizes. 
